            {
              "id": "glog-49c4a8a8-be0b-4ff9-ba42-50893f872457",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluate setTimeout for Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `setTimeout` function is used with a string argument that includes untrusted data. This can lead to code injection attacks, as the string is evaluated as JavaScript code. In the provided code snippet, the `setTimeout` function is used with a function, which is generally safer than using a string. However, if any part of the function's logic involves untrusted data, it can still be vulnerable to injection attacks.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid Using Strings in `setTimeout`**: Always use a function instead of a string when calling `setTimeout`.\n2. **Validate and Sanitize Inputs**: Ensure that any data used within the `setTimeout` function is properly validated and sanitized.\n3. **Use Strict Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implement a CSP that disallows the use of `eval` and similar functions.\n4. **Review and Test Code**: Regularly review and test your code for potential injection vulnerabilities.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code snippet, ensure that the data used within the `setTimeout` function is trusted and properly sanitized. If `e.yearshtml` is derived from user input or any untrusted source, it should be sanitized before use.\n\n```javascript\n// Assuming e.yearshtml is sanitized and trusted\nsetTimeout(function() {\n    if (o === e.yearshtml && e.yearshtml) {\n        e.dpDiv.find(\"select.ui-datepicker-year:first\").replaceWith(e.yearshtml);\n    }\n}, 0);\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet appears to be using jQuery for DOM manipulation. Ensure that jQuery is included in your project:\n\n```html\n<script src=\"https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js\"></script>\n```\n\n### OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)"
              },
