            {
              "id": "glog-bb669444-2c90-44bf-9b86-6fb98aceb665",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluate setTimeout Usage with Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `setTimeout` function is used with untrusted data, potentially leading to code injection attacks. This vulnerability occurs because `setTimeout` can execute a string of code, which, if constructed from untrusted input, can be exploited by an attacker to execute arbitrary code.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `setTimeout` function is used to execute a function that processes data. If any part of this data is derived from untrusted sources, it could lead to security vulnerabilities.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid Using Strings in `setTimeout`:** Always use function references instead of strings in `setTimeout` to prevent code injection.\n2. **Validate and Sanitize Input:** Ensure that all input data is validated and sanitized before use.\n3. **Use Security Libraries:** Consider using libraries that provide security features to help mitigate injection attacks.\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP):** Implement CSP headers to restrict the execution of scripts on your web pages.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using a string in `setTimeout`, use a function reference:\n\n```javascript\nsetTimeout(() => {\n    that.clr.loadData(json);\n    that.data = that.clr.proxyData;\n    callback();\n}, 0);\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided does not explicitly list any library dependencies. However, it assumes the existence of `that.clr` and `callback`, which may be part of a larger application or framework. Ensure that any libraries or frameworks used are up-to-date and maintained.\n\n### OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)\n\nThese resources provide further information on JavaScript security best practices and common vulnerabilities."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS172411"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "glog-97921c7b-c18b-4916-82c7-1fb70fb209ce",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluation of Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `eval()` function is used to execute code that is constructed from untrusted input. This can lead to severe security risks, including code injection attacks, where an attacker can execute arbitrary code on the server or client-side. In the provided code snippet, the `eval()` function is used to execute JavaScript code read from files, which could potentially be manipulated by an attacker if the file paths or contents are not properly validated and sanitized.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid `eval()`**: The best practice is to avoid using `eval()` altogether. If dynamic code execution is necessary, consider safer alternatives such as `Function` constructors or other JavaScript features that do not execute code in the global scope.\n\n2. **Input Validation and Sanitization**: Ensure that any input used to construct file paths or code is properly validated and sanitized. This includes checking for unexpected characters, path traversal attempts, and ensuring that only trusted sources can modify the input.\n\n3. **Use Static Code Analysis**: Employ static code analysis tools to detect and prevent the use of `eval()` and other potentially dangerous functions in your codebase.\n\n4. **File Integrity Checks**: Implement file integrity checks to ensure that the contents of the files being read have not been tampered with.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `eval()` with a safer alternative. If the code execution is necessary, consider using a JavaScript engine that can execute code in a sandboxed environment. Here's an example of how you might refactor the code to avoid using `eval()`:\n\n```javascript\nconst vm = require('vm');\nconst fs = require('fs');\n\nfunction executeFile(filePath) {\n    const code = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8');\n    const script = new vm.Script(code);\n    const context = vm.createContext({});\n    script.runInContext(context);\n}\n\nconst files = [\n    'lib.js',\n    'ometa-base.js',\n    'bs-js-compiler.js',\n    'bs-ometa-js-compiler.js',\n    'bs-ometa-compiler.js',\n    'bs-ometa-optimizer.js'\n];\n\nfiles.forEach(file => executeFile(ometaPath + file));\n\nlet ometaEval = '';\nconst macroFiles = [\n    \"expr.ometa\",\n    \"exprGen.ometa\",\n    \"ftl.ometa\",\n    \"traits.ometa\",\n    \"renderExp.ometa\",\n    \"renderAndTraits.ometa\",\n    \"reorder.ometa\"\n];\n\nmacroFiles.forEach(file => {\n    ometaEval += fs.readFileSync(macroPath + file, 'utf8') + '\\n\\n';\n});\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nTo execute the refactored code, the following Node.js core modules are required:\n\n- `fs`: File System module to read files.\n- `vm`: Virtual Machine module to execute code in a sandboxed environment.\n\n### Relevant OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS189424"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "glog-e993e1dd-90a9-49df-be00-7ee3d76e6ef8",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluate setTimeout Usage with Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `setTimeout` function is used with untrusted data, potentially leading to code injection attacks. This vulnerability occurs because `setTimeout` can execute a string of code, which, if constructed from untrusted input, can be exploited by attackers to execute arbitrary code in the context of the web application.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid Using Strings in `setTimeout`:** Always use function references instead of strings when calling `setTimeout`.\n2. **Validate and Sanitize Input:** Ensure that any data used in conjunction with `setTimeout` is properly validated and sanitized.\n3. **Use Security Libraries:** Consider using libraries that provide safer alternatives or wrappers for `setTimeout`.\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP):** Implement CSP headers to restrict the execution of inline scripts.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nFor the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```javascript\nsetTimeout(function(cb) {\n    sc.layoutAndRenderAsync(cb);\n}, 1000);\n```\n\nEnsure that the callback function is defined and passed safely without using untrusted data:\n\n```javascript\nfunction safeCallback() {\n    sc.layoutAndRenderAsync(function() {\n        // Callback logic here\n    });\n}\n\nsetTimeout(safeCallback, 1000);\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not specify any particular library dependencies. However, if `sc.layoutAndRenderAsync` is part of a specific library, ensure that the library is properly included in your project.\n\n### OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS172411"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "glog-f65bcd34-6f5c-42e9-9c6b-e9540d6c451d",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluate setTimeout Usage with Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `setTimeout` function is used with untrusted data, potentially leading to code injection attacks. This vulnerability occurs because `setTimeout` can execute a string of JavaScript code, which, if constructed from untrusted input, can be exploited by attackers to execute arbitrary code.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid Using Strings in `setTimeout`:** Always use function references instead of strings when calling `setTimeout`.\n2. **Validate and Sanitize Input:** Ensure that any data used in conjunction with `setTimeout` is properly validated and sanitized.\n3. **Use Strict Content Security Policy (CSP):** Implement a strict CSP to prevent the execution of malicious scripts.\n4. **Use Security Libraries:** Consider using libraries that help in sanitizing and validating inputs.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n#### Vulnerable Code\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable: Using untrusted data in setTimeout\nsetTimeout(function() {\n    eval(untrustedInput);\n}, 1000);\n```\n\n#### Fixed Code\n\n```javascript\n// Secure: Using a function reference instead of a string\nsetTimeout(function() {\n    // Safely handle the untrusted input\n    console.log('Executing safe code');\n}, 1000);\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n### Relevant OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)\n\nThese resources and links are valid and accessible to anonymous users as of the latest check."
              },
